Nelson stole Murdock's keys and broke into his apartment to get his [[Daredevil's Suit|Daredevil Suit]]. When Murdock was talking to Cage and Jones, Nelson barged in, telling him he needed to talk. He warned Murdock that his personal life and vigilante life were very close to colliding. However, Nelson knew he couldn't talk Murdock out of it and gave him a bag containing the suit. Murdock then escaped with Jones and Cage. Nelson found Page and told her that he gave Murdock the suit. He explained that if Murdock finishes this, they will hopefully get their friend back. Suddenly, the power went out, and Nelson exclaimed that it could not be good.{{Ref|TD107}}

====Close Loss====
{{Quote|I always knew those lives would get [[Matt Murdock|him]] killed. And in the end, I actually helped him get to that [[Midland Circle|building]]. In the [[Daredevil's Suit|suit]], no less."<br>"If you would have been there, you would have seen... You made the right call."<br>"I can't help but feel like I didn't.|Foggy Nelson and [[Claire Temple]]|The Defenders (episode)}}
Foggy Nelson got word that the [[Defenders]] were spotted at [[Midland Circle]]. He told [[Karen Page]] and [[Trish Walker]]. Walker informed them that it was the center of the earthquake a few nights ago. As the battle commenced, Nelson and the rest listened to the radio. Later, Midland had collapsed, meaning the end of the [[Hand]]. Nelson and Page watched as the Defenders returned to the precinct, embracing their loved ones. The two waited for Murdock, only for him not to return. Page cried into Nelson's arms as he hugged her. But he couldn't stop staring at the door, hoping his friend would make it back and knowing it was his fault.

In the following days, Nelson and his firm cleared every one of their charges. He told [[Luke Cage]] and [[Claire Temple]] the news. Cage told him he was sorry for his loss. Nelson replied that it was all of their losses. As he left, Temple caught up with him. Nelson admitted he made the wrong choice. Temple explained that she didn't know Murdock as well as Nelson, but there was no talking him down. He loved the [[Hell's Kitchen|city]] more than he loved himself.

